## PART 2: MORE COMPILATION ERRORS

### Q11. What is "constructor is already defined" error?

You cannot have two constructors with the exact same parameter list (same type, same order).

```java
public class Employee {
    String name;
    int age;
    
    public Employee(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }
    
    // Error: constructor Employee(String,int) is already defined
    public Employee(String empName, int empAge) {
        this.name = empName;
        this.age = empAge;
    }
}
```

**Why?** Java can't decide which constructor to call. Even though parameter names are different (name vs empName), the types are identical - both are (String, int).

**This is fine (different parameter types):**
```java
public Employee(String name, int age) { }
public Employee(String name) { }  // Fine - different parameter count
public Employee(int id, String name) { } // Fine - different order
```

**Industry example:** In a Product class for e-commerce, if you create two constructors both taking (String name, double price), Java won't compile. You need to make them different - maybe one takes (String, double) and another takes (String, double, int quantity).

---

### Q12. What is "array required, but X found" error?

You're trying to use array syntax on something that's not an array.

```java
String name = "John";
System.out.println(name[0]); // Error: array required, but String found

int age = 25;
System.out.println(age[0]); // Error: array required, but int found
```

**Common mistake in loops:**
```java
String userName = "admin";
for(int i = 0; i < userName.length(); i++) {
    System.out.println(userName[i]); // Error!
}

// Correct way:
System.out.println(userName.charAt(i));
```

**Industry example:** In a password validation service, if you try to access characters of a String password using array notation password[0] instead of password.charAt(0), you'll get this error. Coming from languages like Python, this is a common mistake.

