### Q17. What is "abstract method cannot have a body" error?

Abstract methods are meant to be implemented by subclasses, so they cannot have implementation in the abstract class.

```java
public abstract class Payment {
    public abstract void processPayment() { // Error: abstract methods cannot have a body
        System.out.println("Processing");
    }
}

// Correct way:
public abstract class Payment {
    public abstract void processPayment(); // Just signature, no body
}

public class CreditCardPayment extends Payment {
    public void processPayment() { // Implementation here
        System.out.println("Processing credit card");
    }
}
```

**Industry example:** In a payment gateway, you have an abstract Payment class with processPayment() method. Each payment type (CreditCard, DebitCard, UPI) implements it differently. The abstract method must be empty - no body allowed.

---

### Q18. What is "class X is public, should be declared in a file named X.java" error?

If a class is declared public, it MUST be in a file with the exact same name.

```java
// File name: Test.java
public class Employee { // Error: class Employee is public, should be declared in Employee.java
    String name;
}
```

**Rules:**
- One public class per file
- File name must match public class name exactly (case-sensitive)
- You can have multiple non-public classes in same file

```java
// File name: Employee.java - This is correct
public class Employee {
    String name;
}

class Department { // Fine - not public
    String name;
}

class Address { // Fine - not public
    String city;
}
```

**Industry example:** In a microservice project, if you create a public class CustomerService but save the file as Service.java, compilation fails. IDE usually creates files with correct names, but if you manually create files, this error can occur.

