### Q19. What is "break outside switch or loop" error?

The break statement can only be used inside loops (for, while) or switch statements.

```java
public void processData() {
    System.out.println("Start");
    break; // Error: break outside switch or loop
    System.out.println("End");
}

// Common mistake:
if(condition) {
    break; // Error: break doesn't work in if statements
}
```

**Correct usage:**
```java
for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if(i == 5) {
        break; // Fine - inside loop
    }
}

switch(status) {
    case "ACTIVE":
        System.out.println("Active");
        break; // Fine - inside switch
}
```

**Industry example:** In a data processing job, if you want to exit early based on a condition, you can't just put break in an if statement. You need to use return (to exit method) or restructure with a loop.

---

### Q20. What is "continue outside of loop" error?

Similar to break, continue can only be used inside loops.

```java
public void validateOrders() {
    if(order.isValid()) {
        continue; // Error: continue outside of loop
    }
}

// Correct usage:
for(Order order : orders) {
    if(!order.isValid()) {
        continue; // Fine - skip this iteration
    }
    processOrder(order);
}
```

**Industry example:** In a batch job processing orders, if an order is invalid, you use continue to skip it and move to the next one. But continue only makes sense inside a loop context.

