## PART 3: RUNTIME EXCEPTIONS (UNCHECKED)

### Q21. What is NullPointerException and when does it occur?

This is THE most common runtime exception. It happens when you try to use an object reference that points to null.

**Common scenarios:**

**Scenario 1 - Calling method on null:**
```java
String name = null;
System.out.println(name.length()); // NullPointerException
```

**Scenario 2 - Accessing array element when array is null:**
```java
int[] numbers = null;
System.out.println(numbers[0]); // NullPointerException
```

**Scenario 3 - Uninitialized object fields:**
```java
public class Employee {
    Address address; // null by default
    
    public void printCity() {
        System.out.println(address.city); // NullPointerException if address not initialized
    }
}
```

**Scenario 4 - Method returning null:**
```java
public Employee findEmployee(int id) {
    // Database query finds nothing
    return null;
}

Employee emp = findEmployee(999);
System.out.println(emp.getName()); // NullPointerException
```

**Prevention:**
```java
if(name != null) {
    System.out.println(name.length());
}

// Or modern approach:
String result = (name != null) ? name.toUpperCase() : "DEFAULT";
```

**Industry example:** In an e-commerce app, when fetching user's shipping address, if user hasn't added address yet, the query returns null. If you directly try to access address.getCity() without null check, application crashes with NullPointerException. This is why you always validate: `if(address != null)` before accessing.

