### Q30. What is ConcurrentModificationException?

This happens when you modify a collection while iterating over it (in most cases).

```java
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();
names.add("John");
names.add("Mary");
names.add("Bob");

for(String name : names) {
    if(name.equals("Mary")) {
        names.remove(name); // ConcurrentModificationException
    }
}
```

**Why?** The iterator detects that the collection was modified during iteration and throws this fail-fast exception.

**Correct approaches:**

**Approach 1 - Use Iterator's remove:**
```java
Iterator<String> iterator = names.iterator();
while(iterator.hasNext()) {
    String name = iterator.next();
    if(name.equals("Mary")) {
        iterator.remove(); // Safe
    }
}
```

**Approach 2 - Collect items to remove:**
```java
List<String> toRemove = new ArrayList<>();
for(String name : names) {
    if(name.equals("Mary")) {
        toRemove.add(name);
    }
}
names.removeAll(toRemove);
```

**Industry example:** In a notification service, you have a list of subscribers. While sending notifications in a loop, if you remove unsubscribed users directly in the loop, you get ConcurrentModificationException. Solution: collect unsubscribed users first, then remove them after the loop.

