### Q48. What is the finally block and when does it execute?

Finally block ALWAYS executes, whether exception occurs or not, whether exception is caught or not.

```java
try {
    System.out.println("Try block");
    int x = 10 / 0; // Exception
} catch(ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Catch block");
} finally {
    System.out.println("Finally block - ALWAYS executes");
}

// Output:
// Try block
// Catch block
// Finally block - ALWAYS executes
```

**Even if no exception:**
```java
try {
    System.out.println("Try block");
    return;
} finally {
    System.out.println("Finally executes even after return!");
}
```

**Common use case - Resource cleanup:**
```java
Connection conn = null;
try {
    conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, password);
    // Database operations
} catch(SQLException e) {
    System.out.println("Database error");
} finally {
    if(conn != null) {
        try {
            conn.close(); // Always close connection
        } catch(SQLException e) {
            // Log error
        }
    }
}
```

**When finally doesn't execute (very rare):**
- JVM crashes: `System.exit(0)`
- Fatal errors
- Infinite loop in try/catch

**Industry example:** In a file processing service, you open a file in try block. Whether processing succeeds or fails (exception), you MUST close the file in finally block to release resources. Without finally, if exception occurs, file remains open (resource leak).

