### Q49. What is try-with-resources and how is it better than finally?

Try-with-resources automatically closes resources that implement AutoCloseable interface. No need for finally block.

**Old way with finally:**
```java
BufferedReader br = null;
try {
    br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"));
    String line = br.readLine();
} catch(IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Error");
} finally {
    if(br != null) {
        try {
            br.close(); // Manual closing
        } catch(IOException e) {
            // Handle close error
        }
    }
}
```

**New way with try-with-resources:**
```java
try(BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"))) {
    String line = br.readLine();
} catch(IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Error");
}
// BufferedReader automatically closed - no finally needed!
```

**Multiple resources:**
```java
try(
    FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("input.txt");
    FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream("output.txt")
) {
    // Use both streams
    // Both automatically closed in reverse order
} catch(IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Error");
}
```

**Benefits:**
1. Less code - no finally needed
2. Safer - resources always closed, even if exception in close() itself
3. Resources closed in reverse order of creation

**Industry example:** In a database service, instead of manually closing Connection, Statement, ResultSet in finally block, you use try-with-resources. If any error occurs during close operations, try-with-resources handles it gracefully, preventing resource leaks.

