### Q51. Can we throw multiple exceptions from a method?

Yes! A method can throw multiple exception types.

```java
public void processOrder(Order order) throws SQLException, IOException, ValidationException {
    // Validate order
    if(!isValid(order)) {
        throw new ValidationException("Invalid order");
    }
    
    // Save to database
    saveToDatabase(order); // might throw SQLException
    
    // Generate invoice PDF
    generateInvoice(order); // might throw IOException
}
```

**Caller must handle all declared exceptions:**
```java
try {
    processOrder(order);
} catch(SQLException e) {
    System.out.println("Database error");
} catch(IOException e) {
    System.out.println("File error");
} catch(ValidationException e) {
    System.out.println("Validation error");
}
```

**Or declare throws in caller too:**
```java
public void handleOrder(Order order) throws SQLException, IOException, ValidationException {
    processOrder(order); // Propagating exceptions up
}
```

**Industry example:** In a payment processing method, you might throw PaymentDeclinedException (card declined), NetworkException (payment gateway unreachable), InsufficientBalanceException (not enough money). Each exception type indicates different failure reason, allowing caller to handle each appropriately.

