### Q54. Can we re-throw an exception?

Yes! You can catch an exception and throw it again (or throw a different exception).

**Re-throwing same exception:**
```java
public void processData() throws IOException {
    try {
        // File operations
        readFile();
    } catch(IOException e) {
        // Log the error
        logger.error("File error: " + e.getMessage());
        
        // Re-throw for caller to handle
        throw e;
    }
}
```

**Throwing different exception:**
```java
public void processOrder() throws OrderException {
    try {
        // Database operation
        saveOrder();
    } catch(SQLException e) {
        // Convert to business exception
        throw new OrderException("Order processing failed", e);
    }
}
```

**Why re-throw?**
1. Log exception locally but let caller handle it
2. Add additional context
3. Convert technical exception to business exception

**Partial handling:**
```java
public void importData() throws DataException {
    try {
        processFile();
    } catch(IOException e) {
        if(isRecoverable(e)) {
            // Handle locally
            retry();
        } else {
            // Can't handle, re-throw
            throw new DataException("Fatal error", e);
        }
    }
}
```

**Industry example:** In a batch job, when processing fails for a record, you catch the exception, log it with record details (for debugging), update statistics (failed count), and re-throw the exception so the job coordinator knows processing failed and can decide whether to abort or continue.

