## PART 9: GLOBAL EXCEPTION HANDLING

### Q59. What is global exception handling and why do we need it?

Global exception handling is a centralized way to handle all exceptions in one place instead of try-catch in every method.

**Without global handling (bad):**
```java
@RestController
public class UserController {
    
    @GetMapping("/users/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<?> getUser(@PathVariable int id) {
        try {
            User user = userService.getUser(id);
            return ResponseEntity.ok(user);
        } catch(UserNotFoundException e) {
            return ResponseEntity.status(404).body("User not found");
        } catch(Exception e) {
            return ResponseEntity.status(500).body("Server error");
        }
    }
    
    @PostMapping("/users")
    public ResponseEntity<?> createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        try {
            User created = userService.create(user);
            return ResponseEntity.ok(created);
        } catch(DuplicateEmailException e) {
            return ResponseEntity.status(400).body("Email already exists");
        } catch(Exception e) {
            return ResponseEntity.status(500).body("Server error");
        }
    }
    // Same try-catch in every method!
}
```

**Problems:**
1. Code duplication
2. Hard to maintain
3. Inconsistent error responses
4. Cluttered business logic

**With global handling (good):**
```java
@RestController
public class UserController {
    
    @GetMapping("/users/{id}")
    public User getUser(@PathVariable int id) {
        return userService.getUser(id); // No try-catch!
    }
    
    @PostMapping("/users")
    public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        return userService.create(user); // No try-catch!
    }
}

@ControllerAdvice // Global exception handler
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {
    
    @ExceptionHandler(UserNotFoundException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<String> handleUserNotFound(UserNotFoundException e) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(404).body(e.getMessage());
    }
    
    @ExceptionHandler(DuplicateEmailException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<String> handleDuplicateEmail(DuplicateEmailException e) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(400).body(e.getMessage());
    }
    
    @ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
    public ResponseEntity<String> handleGeneric(Exception e) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(500).body("Internal server error");
    }
}
```

**Benefits:**
1. Clean controller code
2. Centralized exception handling
3. Consistent error responses
4. Easy to maintain

**Industry example:** In your PerformanceTrack Analytics module, instead of wrapping every analytics calculation in try-catch, you let exceptions bubble up to global handler. Global handler catches GoalNotFoundException and returns proper JSON error response with 404 status.

