### Q60. What is @ControllerAdvice annotation in Spring Boot?

@ControllerAdvice marks a class as global exception handler for all controllers.

```java
@ControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {
    
    @ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handleException(Exception e) {
        ErrorResponse error = new ErrorResponse(
            HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR.value(),
            e.getMessage(),
            System.currentTimeMillis()
        );
        return new ResponseEntity<>(error, HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR);
    }
}
```

**How it works:**
1. Spring scans for @ControllerAdvice classes on startup
2. When exception occurs in any controller
3. Spring checks if global handler has @ExceptionHandler for that exception
4. If found, calls that handler method
5. Returns response to client

**Scope control:**
```java
// Handle exceptions only for specific package
@ControllerAdvice(basePackages = "com.example.api.controllers")
public class ApiExceptionHandler { }

// Handle exceptions only for specific controllers
@ControllerAdvice(assignableTypes = {UserController.class, OrderController.class})
public class SpecificExceptionHandler { }

// Handle exceptions only for @RestController
@RestControllerAdvice // Combines @ControllerAdvice + @ResponseBody
public class RestExceptionHandler { }
```

**Industry example:** In your PerformanceTrack system, you have multiple modules (Goals, Reviews, Feedback, Analytics). Instead of handling exceptions in each module separately, one @ControllerAdvice class handles all exceptions from all modules, ensuring consistent error responses across the entire application.

