### Q71. How does exception handling work with transactions (@Transactional)?

By default, Spring rolls back transactions only for unchecked exceptions (RuntimeException and Error).

**Default behavior:**
```java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    
    @Transactional
    public void processOrder(Order order) {
        orderRepository.save(order); // Transaction starts
        
        // Unchecked exception - transaction WILL rollback
        if(order.getAmount() < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid amount");
        }
        
        // Checked exception - transaction will NOT rollback by default!
        try {
            externalService.call();
        } catch(IOException e) {
            throw new IOException("Service unavailable"); // Transaction commits!
        }
    }
}
```

**Configuring rollback for checked exceptions:**
```java
@Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class) // Rollback for all exceptions
public void processOrder(Order order) throws IOException {
    orderRepository.save(order);
    externalService.call(); // If IOException occurs, transaction rolls back
}

// Or specific exceptions
@Transactional(rollbackFor = {IOException.class, SQLException.class})
public void processData() throws IOException, SQLException {
    // Rolls back for IOException or SQLException
}
```

**Preventing rollback for specific exceptions:**
```java
@Transactional(noRollbackFor = ValidationException.class)
public void processOrder(Order order) {
    orderRepository.save(order);
    
    // Even though RuntimeException, transaction won't rollback for ValidationException
    if(!isValid(order)) {
        throw new ValidationException("Invalid order");
    }
}
```

**Nested transactions with exception handling:**
```java
@Transactional
public void processMultipleOrders(List<Order> orders) {
    for(Order order : orders) {
        try {
            processSingleOrder(order); // Has its own @Transactional
        } catch(Exception e) {
            logger.error("Failed to process order: {}", order.getId(), e);
            // Continue with other orders
        }
    }
}

@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
public void processSingleOrder(Order order) {
    // Runs in separate transaction
    // If this fails, only this order rolls back, not parent transaction
}
```

**Industry example:** In PerformanceTrack, when manager approves multiple goals in batch, you wrap each goal approval in separate transaction with REQUIRES_NEW. If one goal approval fails (maybe foreign key violation), only that goal rolls back. Other goals are still approved. You catch exception, log "Goal ID 123 approval failed", and continue with remaining goals.

