### Q73. Can we have try without catch or finally?

**No! Try must have either catch or finally (or both).**

**Invalid - won't compile:**
```java
try {
    int x = 10 / 0;
}
// Error: 'try' without 'catch', 'finally' or resource declarations
```

**Valid options:**

**Option 1 - try-catch:**
```java
try {
    int x = 10 / 0;
} catch(ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Error");
}
```

**Option 2 - try-finally:**
```java
try {
    int x = 10 / 0;
} finally {
    System.out.println("Cleanup");
}
// Exception still propagates up, but finally executes
```

**Option 3 - try-catch-finally:**
```java
try {
    int x = 10 / 0;
} catch(ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Error");
} finally {
    System.out.println("Cleanup");
}
```

**Option 4 - try-with-resources (Java 7+):**
```java
try(FileReader fr = new FileReader("file.txt")) {
    // Use resource
}
// No catch or finally needed - resource auto-closed
```

**When to use try-finally without catch?**
When you want to ensure cleanup happens but don't want to handle the exception:

```java
public void processData() throws IOException {
    Lock lock = getLock();
    try {
        lock.acquire();
        // Process data
    } finally {
        lock.release(); // Always release lock
    }
    // IOException propagates to caller
}
```

**Industry example:** In PerformanceTrack, when generating PDF report, you acquire a file lock to prevent concurrent access. You use try-finally to ensure lock is released even if PDF generation fails. You don't catch the exception because you want it to propagate up to the global handler which will return appropriate HTTP error response.

