### Q75. What happens when exception occurs in catch block?

The exception in catch block propagates up, and the original exception is lost (unless you chain them).

**Exception in catch block:**
```java
try {
    int x = 10 / 0; // ArithmeticException
} catch(ArithmeticException e) {
    int y = 10 / 0; // Another ArithmeticException!
    // Original exception lost, this new exception propagates
}
```

**Better approach - log before throwing:**
```java
try {
    int x = 10 / 0;
} catch(ArithmeticException e) {
    logger.error("Original error", e); // Log original
    
    // Now if something fails here, at least original is logged
    notifyAdmin(e);
}
```

**Exception in catch with exception chaining:**
```java
try {
    processOrder();
} catch(OrderException e) {
    try {
        rollbackOrder();
    } catch(RollbackException rollbackEx) {
        // Chain both exceptions
        throw new SystemException("Order processing failed and rollback failed", e)
            .addSuppressed(rollbackEx);
    }
}
```

**Real-world scenario:**
```java
Connection conn = null;
try {
    conn = getConnection();
    // Database operations
} catch(SQLException e) {
    logger.error("Database error", e);
    throw new DataAccessException("DB operation failed", e);
} finally {
    if(conn != null) {
        try {
            conn.close();
        } catch(SQLException closeEx) {
            // Exception while closing!
            logger.error("Failed to close connection", closeEx);
            // Don't throw here - would hide original exception
        }
    }
}
```

**Industry example:** In PerformanceTrack, when saving a goal fails, you try to send notification email to admin about the failure. If email sending also fails (in catch block), you don't want to lose the original "goal save failed" error. You log the email error separately but rethrow the original goal save exception.

