### Q81. How do we handle exceptions when using Java Streams?

Streams don't handle checked exceptions well. You need workarounds.

**Problem - Checked exception in lambda:**
```java
List<String> files = Arrays.asList("file1.txt", "file2.txt", "file3.txt");

// Won't compile - FileReader throws IOException
files.stream()
    .map(file -> new FileReader(file)) // Compile error!
    .forEach(reader -> processFile(reader));
```

**Solution 1 - Wrap in unchecked exception:**
```java
files.stream()
    .map(file -> {
        try {
            return new FileReader(file);
        } catch(IOException e) {
            throw new UncheckedIOException(e); // Wrap in unchecked
        }
    })
    .forEach(reader -> processFile(reader));
```

**Solution 2 - Create utility wrapper:**
```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface ThrowingFunction<T, R> {
    R apply(T t) throws Exception;
    
    static <T, R> Function<T, R> wrap(ThrowingFunction<T, R> throwingFunction) {
        return t -> {
            try {
                return throwingFunction.apply(t);
            } catch(Exception e) {
                throw new RuntimeException(e);
            }
        };
    }
}

// Usage:
files.stream()
    .map(ThrowingFunction.wrap(file -> new FileReader(file)))
    .forEach(reader -> processFile(reader));
```

**Solution 3 - Handle exceptions within stream:**
```java
List<String> results = files.stream()
    .map(file -> {
        try {
            FileReader reader = new FileReader(file);
            return processFile(reader);
        } catch(IOException e) {
            logger.error("Failed to process file: {}", file, e);
            return null; // or default value
        }
    })
    .filter(Objects::nonNull) // Remove nulls (failed items)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
```

**Solution 4 - Collect exceptions separately:**
```java
List<String> files = Arrays.asList("file1.txt", "file2.txt", "file3.txt");
List<Exception> errors = new ArrayList<>();

List<String> results = files.stream()
    .map(file -> {
        try {
            return processFile(file);
        } catch(Exception e) {
            errors.add(e);
            return null;
        }
    })
    .filter(Objects::nonNull)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

if(!errors.isEmpty()) {
    logger.error("Processing completed with {} errors", errors.size());
    errors.forEach(e -> logger.error("Error: ", e));
}
```

**Industry example:** In PerformanceTrack Analytics, you calculate goal completion rate for all departments using streams. If one department's calculation fails (maybe data corruption), you don't want entire stream to fail. You wrap in try-catch, log error for that department, return null/default value, and continue with other departments. Final report shows "HR: 85%, Sales: 92%, IT: Data unavailable".

