### Q82. What is the performance impact of exception handling?

Exception handling has performance cost. Understanding this helps write efficient code.

**Performance considerations:**

**1. Creating exceptions is expensive:**
```java
// Expensive - creates stack trace
throw new Exception("Error");

// Less expensive - no stack trace (but loses debugging info)
throw new Exception("Error", null, false, false);
```

**2. Don't use exceptions for control flow:**
```java
// Very bad - exception for normal flow
public User findUser(String email) {
    try {
        return database.getUser(email);
    } catch(UserNotFoundException e) {
        return createDefaultUser();
    }
}

// Good - use conditional logic
public User findUser(String email) {
    Optional<User> user = database.getUser(email);
    return user.orElseGet(() -> createDefaultUser());
}
```

**3. Catching exceptions is cheap, throwing is expensive:**
```java
// Try-catch has minimal overhead if no exception occurs
try {
    normalOperation(); // Fast
} catch(Exception e) {
    // Not executed - no cost
}

// But throwing is expensive
for(int i = 0; i < 1000000; i++) {
    try {
        throw new Exception(); // Very slow!
    } catch(Exception e) {
        // Handle
    }
}
```

**4. Deep call stacks increase exception cost:**
```java
// Expensive - exception travels through 10 method calls
public void method1() {
    try {
        method2();
    } catch(Exception e) {
        // Exception traveled through 10 methods to get here
    }
}

public void method2() { method3(); }
public void method3() { method4(); }
// ... method4 to method9
public void method10() {
    throw new Exception(); // Created here, caught 10 levels up
}
```

**5. Validation before operations:**
```java
// Bad - relying on exception
public void processFile(String path) {
    try {
        FileReader fr = new FileReader(path);
        // Process
    } catch(FileNotFoundException e) {
        logger.error("File not found");
    }
}

// Better - validate first
public void processFile(String path) {
    File file = new File(path);
    if(!file.exists()) {
        logger.error("File not found");
        return;
    }
    
    try {
        FileReader fr = new FileReader(path);
        // Process
    } catch(IOException e) {
        // Only for unexpected IO errors
    }
}
```

**Benchmark example:**
```java
// Throwing exceptions: ~5000 nanoseconds per iteration
for(int i = 0; i < 100000; i++) {
    try {
        throw new Exception();
    } catch(Exception e) { }
}

// Conditional logic: ~2 nanoseconds per iteration
for(int i = 0; i < 100000; i++) {
    if(someCondition) {
        // Handle
    }
}
```

**Industry example:** In PerformanceTrack, when checking if goal exists before updating, don't call `updateGoal()` and catch GoalNotFoundException. First check `if(goalRepository.existsById(id))`, then call update. For 10,000 goals processed in batch, this saves significant time - validation is microseconds, exceptions are milliseconds.

