### Q83. How do we handle exceptions in CompletableFuture chains?

CompletableFuture has special methods for exception handling in async chains.

**Basic exception handling:**
```java
CompletableFuture<String> future = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    if(someCondition) {
        throw new RuntimeException("Error occurred");
    }
    return "Success";
});

// Handle exception
future.exceptionally(ex -> {
    logger.error("Async operation failed", ex);
    return "Default value"; // Fallback
}).thenAccept(result -> {
    System.out.println("Result: " + result);
});
```

**Using handle() - for both success and failure:**
```java
CompletableFuture<String> future = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    return processData();
})
.handle((result, ex) -> {
    if(ex != null) {
        logger.error("Processing failed", ex);
        return "Error: " + ex.getMessage();
    }
    return "Success: " + result;
});
```

**Exception in chain:**
```java
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    return "Step 1";
})
.thenApply(result -> {
    throw new RuntimeException("Error in step 2");
})
.thenApply(result -> {
    return "Step 3"; // Won't execute
})
.exceptionally(ex -> {
    logger.error("Chain failed at some step", ex);
    return "Failed";
});
```

**Multiple futures with exception handling:**
```java
CompletableFuture<String> future1 = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> service1.call());
CompletableFuture<String> future2 = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> service2.call());
CompletableFuture<String> future3 = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> service3.call());

CompletableFuture<Void> allFutures = CompletableFuture.allOf(future1, future2, future3);

allFutures.handle((result, ex) -> {
    if(ex != null) {
        logger.error("At least one future failed", ex);
    }
    
    // Check each future individually
    try {
        String result1 = future1.join();
        logger.info("Service 1: {}", result1);
    } catch(Exception e) {
        logger.error("Service 1 failed", e);
    }
    
    try {
        String result2 = future2.join();
        logger.info("Service 2: {}", result2);
    } catch(Exception e) {
        logger.error("Service 2 failed", e);
    }
    
    return null;
});
```

**Timeout with exception:**
```java
CompletableFuture<String> future = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    // Long running operation
    Thread.sleep(10000);
    return "Done";
});

future.orTimeout(5, TimeUnit.SECONDS) // Throws TimeoutException after 5 seconds
    .exceptionally(ex -> {
        if(ex instanceof TimeoutException) {
            logger.error("Operation timed out");
            return "Timeout";
        }
        return "Error";
    });
```

**Industry example:** In PerformanceTrack Analytics, when generating comprehensive report, you call 5 microservices in parallel (goals, reviews, feedback, attendance, skills). Each call is a CompletableFuture. If one service fails, you use exceptionally() to provide default data for that section. Report still generates with partial data and note "Skills data unavailable". Users get report faster, and one service failure doesn't block entire report.

