### Q86. How do we handle exceptions when calling external microservices?

When calling external services, you need to handle network failures, timeouts, and service unavailability.

**Problem - Direct call without handling:**
```java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    
    @Autowired
    private RestTemplate restTemplate;
    
    public PaymentResponse processPayment(Order order) {
        // What if payment service is down?
        // What if network timeout?
        // What if service returns 500?
        return restTemplate.postForObject(
            "http://payment-service/api/payments",
            order,
            PaymentResponse.class
        );
    }
}
```

**Solution 1 - Try-catch with specific handling:**
```java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    
    public PaymentResponse processPayment(Order order) {
        try {
            return restTemplate.postForObject(
                "http://payment-service/api/payments",
                order,
                PaymentResponse.class
            );
        } catch(ResourceAccessException e) {
            // Network error, timeout
            logger.error("Payment service unreachable", e);
            throw new ServiceUnavailableException("Payment service is currently unavailable");
        } catch(HttpClientErrorException e) {
            // 4xx errors (400, 404, etc.)
            logger.error("Payment service client error: {}", e.getStatusCode());
            throw new PaymentValidationException("Invalid payment request: " + e.getResponseBodyAsString());
        } catch(HttpServerErrorException e) {
            // 5xx errors (500, 503, etc.)
            logger.error("Payment service error: {}", e.getStatusCode());
            throw new PaymentServiceException("Payment service encountered an error");
        } catch(RestClientException e) {
            // Generic REST client errors
            logger.error("Payment service communication error", e);
            throw new ServiceCommunicationException("Failed to communicate with payment service");
        }
    }
}
```

**Solution 2 - RestTemplate with timeout configuration:**
```java
@Configuration
public class RestTemplateConfig {
    
    @Bean
    public RestTemplate restTemplate() {
        SimpleClientHttpRequestFactory factory = new SimpleClientHttpRequestFactory();
        factory.setConnectTimeout(5000); // 5 seconds to establish connection
        factory.setReadTimeout(10000);   // 10 seconds to read response
        
        RestTemplate restTemplate = new RestTemplate(factory);
        
        // Add error handler
        restTemplate.setErrorHandler(new CustomResponseErrorHandler());
        
        return restTemplate;
    }
}

public class CustomResponseErrorHandler implements ResponseErrorHandler {
    
    @Override
    public boolean hasError(ClientHttpResponse response) throws IOException {
        return response.getStatusCode().is4xxClientError() || 
               response.getStatusCode().is5xxServerError();
    }
    
    @Override
    public void handleError(ClientHttpResponse response) throws IOException {
        if(response.getStatusCode().is5xxServerError()) {
            throw new ServiceUnavailableException(
                "External service error: " + response.getStatusCode()
            );
        } else if(response.getStatusCode().is4xxClientError()) {
            throw new InvalidRequestException(
                "Invalid request: " + response.getStatusCode()
            );
        }
    }
}
```

**Solution 3 - Using Feign Client with fallback:**
```java
@FeignClient(
    name = "payment-service",
    fallback = PaymentServiceFallback.class
)
public interface PaymentServiceClient {
    
    @PostMapping("/api/payments")
    PaymentResponse processPayment(@RequestBody PaymentRequest request);
}

@Component
public class PaymentServiceFallback implements PaymentServiceClient {
    
    @Override
    public PaymentResponse processPayment(PaymentRequest request) {
        // Fallback when service is down
        logger.error("Payment service unavailable, using fallback");
        
        PaymentResponse response = new PaymentResponse();
        response.setStatus("PENDING");
        response.setMessage("Payment queued for processing");
        
        // Save to retry queue
        paymentQueue.add(request);
        
        return response;
    }
}
```

**Industry example:** In PerformanceTrack, Analytics module calls Goals microservice to fetch goal data. If Goals service is down, instead of crashing, you catch ServiceUnavailableException, return cached analytics data with timestamp "Last updated: 2 hours ago", and show banner "Real-time data temporarily unavailable. Showing cached results."

